This was one of two matches which trialled having two referees in a single match. The other trial was on 8 May 1935 when the Football League team beat West Bromwich Albion 9&lt;U+2013&gt;6 at The Hawthorns.↩
↩
The game took place to aid the Red Cross fund.↩
↩
Due to war damage, Old Trafford was closed at the time, and Manchester United were playing their home matches at Maine Road. However, on the same day, Manchester City were at home to Chelsea in another FA Cup tie and as a result this tie was switched to Goodison Park.↩
↩
↩
This was the first time that England had been beaten at home by a team from outside the Home Nations.↩
